---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Distance ladder (cosmic distance measurement)";
import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Distance ladder</h1>

    <p>
      The <strong>cosmic distance ladder</strong> is a sequence of methods for measuring distances to increasingly distant objects in the universe. It begins with local anchors (parallax from Gaia) and builds via a series of rungs using different distance indicators.
    </p>

    <h2>Classical rungs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Parallax:</strong> Gaia parallaxes for nearby stars and clusters (local anchor)</li>
      <li><strong>Cepheid variables:</strong> Period-luminosity relation; used to calibrate SN Ia distances</li>
      <li><strong>RR Lyrae:</strong> Alternative to Cepheids for metal-poor populations</li>
      <li><strong>TRGB:</strong> Population II distance indicator; independent check on the Cepheid ladder</li>
      <li><strong>SBF (Surface Brightness Fluctuation):</strong> Extends to more distant galaxies</li>
      <li><strong>Type Ia supernovae:</strong> Standardizable candles for cosmological distances</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Current efforts</h2>
    <p>
      Precise calibration of each rung is essential for measuring the Hubble constant H₀. Chazov et al. (2026) refine the TRGB rung using JWST observations, reducing systematic uncertainties and improving agreement with other H₀ measurements<sup><a href="/pages/chazov_2026_trgb_jwst">1</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>Chazov M. I., et al. (2026). arXiv:2603.11160.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
